Fig. 6
 gives the XPS spectra of samples. For the TNT and S@TNT, the C/Ti atomic ratio is 0.08 and 0.10 (seeing Table 2
), which could be ascribed to the surface carbonaceous contamination. The C 1s spectra is deconvoluted into three peaks that are located at binding energies of 284.5±0.2 eV, 285.5±0.3eV, and 288.7±0.2eV. These peaks are associated with sp2 bonds of graphitic carbon, CO bond (ketone/aldehyde), and OCO groups (carboxyl/ester), respectively [36]. In several documents elsewhere [23,25], they attributed the shoulder at 285.5eV to the incorporation of carbon into the interstitial position of TiO2 lattice [37]. The peak of CO bond becomes more prominent in the CS@TNT, suggesting that part of carbon atom is doped into the frame work of TiO2 during calcination. It can be expected that the band gap of TiO2 could be modulated by the doped C, as reported by several documents [18–20].
